n right side","Forms at third lumbar vertebra and ascends on left side","Forms at fourth lumbar vertebra and crosses midline","Forms at first lumbar vertebra and ascends obliquely"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eforms at fifth lumbar vertebra and ascends on right side\u003C/strong\u003E (image) correctly describes the anatomical course of the inferior vena cava. It is formed by the union of the right and left common iliac veins at the level of the fifth lumbar vertebra (L5) and ascends through the posterior abdominal wall on the right side of the vertebral column before passing through the central tendon of the diaphragm at the eighth thoracic vertebra (T8).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms at second lumbar vertebra and ascends centrally\u003C/strong\u003E - Formation occurs lower at L5, and the vessel runs on the right rather than centrally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms at third lumbar vertebra and ascends on left side\u003C/strong\u003E - The inferior vena cava forms at L5, not L3, and ascends on the right side\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms at fourth lumbar vertebra and crosses midline\u003C/strong\u003E - The inferior vena cava maintains its position on the right side and does not cross the midline\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms at first lumbar vertebra and ascends obliquely\u003C/strong\u003E - Formation occurs at L5, not L1, and the ascent is vertical rather than oblique\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The inferior vena cava is formed by the union of the right and left common iliac veins at the level of the fifth lumbar vertebra.","The inferior vena cava ascends through the abdomen on the right side of the vertebral column.","The inferior vena cava passes through the central tendon of the diaphragm at the level of the eighth thoracic vertebra."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cDoppelte Vena cava inferior 55M\u201d by Hellerhoff is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Doppelte_Vena_cava_inferior_55M_-_CT_axial_paracoronar_KM_pv_-_001_-_Annotation.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18472"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21382"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21382"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5Ftct3LSI1NaIznknytP8dhjrhkZF2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5Ftct3LSI1NaIznknytP8dhjrhkZF2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":278}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60739"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T12:41:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T12:42:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11201"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75231"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":